"Eve M.D., Sperow M., Howerton K., Paustian K., Follett R.F.","Predicted impact of management changes on soil carbon storage for each cropland region of the conterminous United States",2002,"Journal of Soil and Water Conservation","57","4",,"196","204",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036629832&partnerID=40&md5=e3acc274e44ebf5ed9dd3d1ca7ef1871","Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States","Eve, M.D., Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States; Sperow, M., Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States; Howerton, K., Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States; Paustian, K., Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States; Follett, R.F., Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO, United States","The exchange of carbon dioxide between the atmosphere, biosphere and pedosphere is an important consideration when assessing agricultural and environmental management or policy decisions and their relationship to climate change. Field experimentation is the best way to gather data, but experimental data are specific to the management, soils and climate that represent the research site. Inadequate field data exist to address all management options across all soil types and climates. We have used the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change inventory approach to estimate changes in soil carbon storage resulting from various land use and management options. We generate a regional assessment of the relative impact of implementing changes in agricultural management on soil carbon storage. For each agricultural region of the United States, we present an estimated annual change in soil carbon storage for each management option. Results should prove especially useful in evaluating management options and tradeoffs.","Carbon dioxide; Carbon sequestration; Global warming; IPCC; Soil organic carbon; Soil quality","agricultural management; carbon sequestration; soil carbon; soil management; United States",,,,,,"Black, A.L., Tanaka, D.L., A conservation tillage-cropping systems study in the Northern Great Plains of the United States (1997) Soil Organic Matter in Temperate Agroecosystems: Long-term Experiments in North America, pp. 335-342. , E.A. Paul, K. Paustian, E.T. Elliott, and C.V. Cole (editors). CRC Press. Boca Raton, Fla; Blevins, R.L., Lal, R., Doran, J.W., Langdale, G.W., Frye, W.W., Conservation tillage for erosion control and soil quality (1998) Advances in Soil and Water Conservation, , F.J. Pierce and W.W. Frye (editors). Sleeping Bear Press. Ann Arbor, Mich. 239 pp; Bremer, E., Janzen, H.H., Johnston, A.M., Sensitivity of total, light fraction and mineralizable organic matter to management practices in a Lethbridge soil (1994) Canadian Journal of Soil Science, 74, pp. 131-138; Bruce, J.P., Frome, M., Haites, E., Janzen, H., Lal, R., Paustian, K., Carbon sequestration in soils (1999) Journal of Soil and Water Conservation, 54, pp. 382-389; Buyanovsky, G.A., Wagner, G.H., Carbon cycling in cultivated land and its global significance (1998) Global Change Biology, 4, pp. 131-141; Campbell, C.A., Biederbeck, V.O., Zentner, R.P., Lafond, G.P., Effect of crop rotations and cultural practices on soil organic matter, microbial biomass and respiration in a thin Black Chernozem (1991) Canadian Journal of Soil Science, 71, pp. 363-376; Cihacek, L.J., Ulmer, M.G., Estimated soil organic carbon loss from long-term crop-fallow in the Northern Great Plains of the USA (1995) Advances in Soil Science: Soil Management and Greenhouse Effect, pp. 85-92. , R. Lal, J. Kimble, E. Levine, and B.A. Stewart (editors). CRC Press. Boca Raton, Fla; Cole, C.V., Stewart, J.W.B., Ojima, D.S., Parton, W.J., Schimel, D.S., Modeling land use effects of soil 